^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Okay, we discussed the play. The other thing to discuss is my opening bid. Some people would open 2C, and I would not object. But let me give you my guidelines, plus some general thoughts. First of all, there is the Marty Bergen 4 and 4 rule you can use, when you have a major suit. That rule says if you have 4 quick tricks and 4 "Marty Bergen" losers, then you should open 2C if your suit is a major. "Marty Bergen" losers are different than losing trick count.|
PG| ***** 19 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|In Losing trick Count which is a popular hand evaluation method (LTC), my club suit is 2 losers. In "Marty Bergen" losers, it is how many tricks I am likely to lose opposite a singleton. So, my club suit is probably 3 losers at least. And besides, I don't have a major suit.|
PG| ***** 20 ***** |


AT|

nome: I have difficulty to understand why with Bergen method you have three losers. Your Ace clear cannot lose unless it is ruffed.|
PG| ***** 21 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|If you use "Losing Trick Count" (the method popularized by Ron Klinger), you indeed have two losers. However, Marty Bergen does not use Losing Trick Count in formulating his "4 Quick Tricks/4 Losers" rule for opening 2C. He actually figures out how many losers you are likely to have in a suit. For example, AKJ10 is clearly one loser, whereas AKxx is two losers. With AJ6542 opposite a singleton, assuming the likely 4-2 break, you are likely to lose 3 tricks in the suit (not counting ruffing, Marty is looking at losers in a no trump context). |
PG| ***** 22 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|The easiest way to visualize this is to imagine you cash the ace and play low. If clubs are 4-2, you will lose the K, Q, and 10, for example. So, using Marty Bergen's methods, that is a 3 loser suit.|
PG| ***** 23 ***** |


AT|

nome: Thank you for the explanation.|
PG| ***** 24 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|I use a slightly different guideline. My guideline for opening 2C is if I think I have a reasonable shot at 9 tricks in my hand. So, on this hand I have 3 red tricks. In spades I have maybe 1.5 tricks. That is 4.5. In clubs I have around 4 tricks, opposite a singleton by partner. So, I am probably just short of a 2C opener. If you move a small spade to the club suit then I will open 2C. Also, on border line hands, if my suit is a minor, I tend to be less likely to open 2C, since 5 of a minor is harder to make than 4 of a major. So, I was satisfied opening 1C on this hand.|
